new chimp genome data for comparison to the  

107
00:08:58,980 --> 00:09:04,860
human genome and his report created significant 
discussion among geneticists because it stated,  

108
00:09:04,860 --> 00:09:08,280
"The percentage of nucleotides in the human genome  

109
00:09:08,280 --> 00:09:15,000
that had one-to-one exact matches in the 
chimpanzee genome was 84.38 percent."

110
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:21,000
Whoa! That's quite different from 98.5. 
Now some folks might not recognize the  

111
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:25,080
word nucleotides used in the sentence 
displayed. We'd better define that.

112
00:09:25,080 --> 00:09:31,740
A nucleotide is a basic building block of DNA. 
A nucleotide is composed of three molecules:  

113
00:09:31,740 --> 00:09:34,500
a phosphate, a sugar, for example, ribose,  

114
00:09:34,500 --> 00:09:39,960
and a variable nitrogen-based molecule. There 
are four different types of nucleotides.

115
00:09:39,960 --> 00:09:45,660
Think of nucleotides like alphabetic letters. 
The four nucleotides are combined to make  

116
00:09:45,660 --> 00:09:51,660
words. Words are combined into sentences and 
chapters, which are genes, and other DNA used  

117
00:09:51,660 --> 00:09:57,300
for regulating the operation of cells as they 
manufacture new proteins and other molecules.

118
00:09:57,300 --> 00:10:01,020
The human genome has about 3 billion nucleotides.

119
00:10:01,620 --> 00:10:06,600
About the 2018 report you mentioned, 
published by the evolutionist Richard Buggs,  

120
00:10:06,600 --> 00:10:12,360
it's significant that an independent 
comparison of chimp to human DNA was  

121
00:10:12,360 --> 00:10:18,480
done recently by Jeffrey Tompkins. He earned 
a PhD in genetics from Clemson University in  

122
00:10:18,480 --> 00:10:24,900
1996 and worked in the department of genetics 
and biochemistry at Clemson. Tompkins used a  

123
00:10:24,900 --> 00:10:31,500
different method than bugs for comparing the 
two sets of DNA and reports that he, "aligned 18  

124
00:10:31,500 --> 00:10:38,640
000 random pieces of high-quality chimp DNA 
that were each on average 30 544 letters  

125
00:10:38,640 --> 00:10:43,740
long onto the human genome and several 
different versions of the chimp genome."

126
00:10:43,740 --> 00:10:48,360
He states that the aligned segments 
of chimp DNA were on average only  

127
00:10:48,360 --> 00:10:53,520
84.4 percent identical to human 
DNA, basically the same as Buggs.

128
00:10:53,520 --> 00:10:56,340
Interesting, two different 
approaches and similar results.

129
00:10:56,340 --> 00:11:00,960
Yes. It can't be a coincidence that 
Buggs and Tompkins independently,  

130
00:11:00,960 --> 00:11:06,780
